node.text:
This year, Black Women’s Equal Pay Day is August 3. The date signifies the sad reality that Black women, on average, would have to work 214 extra days to reach the same level of income as that of white, non-Hispanic men in 2020. ⁠
⁠
Regardless of the industry in which they work, Black women in the U.S. typically make just 63 cents for every dollar made by white men, according to the National Women’s Law Center. At this rate, the average Black woman worker will lose out on nearly a million dollars of income over a lifetime of work as compared to a white man. Over the past 30 years, this wage gap has only narrowed by 3 cents. ⁠
⁠
Black workers in the U.S. have always faced discrimination; the COVID-19 pandemic only worsened their hardships. The peak unemployment rate for Black women in 2020 was 16.6% in May 2020. In June 2021, more than 1 in 12 Black women were unemployed, compared to 1 in 19 white men. ⁠
⁠
Activists say it’s important to not just focus on post-pandemic recovery, but to go beyond a ‘return to normal.’ In order to close the wage gap, Black women need stronger policies centered around health coverage, reproductive care, affordable child care, equal pay, minimum wage raises, and state and federal unemployment insurance. ⁠
⁠
Companies can also take action in closing the pay gap by ensuring workers have equal advancement opportunities, more transparently reporting employee salaries, subsidizing child care, and training managers to properly support all of their employees.⁠
⁠
⁠
#BlackWomen #EqualPayDay #BlackWomenEqualPayDay

node.text:
In a guest essay for The New York Times, Alex Azar, former secretary of health and human services, expressed his frustration with vaccine hesitancy.

‘The reluctance and even refusal of many Americans — including many of my fellow conservatives and Republicans — to get a Covid-19 vaccine is a frustrating irony for those of us who worked to expedite these vaccines,’ Azar said, citing the Trump administration’s efforts to fast-track vaccine authorization through Operation Warp Speed.

An Associated Press-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research poll from July highlighted the partisan divide on vaccine hesitancy: 43% of Republicans said they ‘have not been vaccinated and definitely or probably won’t be,’ compared to just 10% of Democrats.

#politics #news #covid_19 #vaccines #misinformation

JACKIE SPEIER (D-CA) ON CNN AUGUST 2021'.

node.text:
Rep. Jackie Speier told CNN's Brian Stelter that she sees similarities between cult leader Jim Jones and former President Donald Trump. Jones commanded a cult known as the Peoples Temple, which fled San Francisco in the 1970s to Guyana. In Guyana, they established their own community, Jonestown. And, coming from Speier personally, that comparison is particularly noteworthy.
In 1978, Speier was a 28-year-old aide to Rep. Leo Ryan of California. Ryan, Speier, and several others traveled to Jonestown to inspect the compound and investigate allegations of abuse against Jones. While there, Ryan and 4 others were shot & killed by members of the cult. Speier herself was shot 5 times but survived. Later that day, Jones and 900+ of his followers drank cyanide-laced Flavor Aid in a mass suicide event that became known as the Jonestown Massacre.
In comparing Trump to Jones, Rep. Speier said the former president was able to 'talk in terms that appealed to those who were disaffected, disillusioned, and who were looking for something,' and described both men as 'merchants of deceit.'
'The only difference between Jim Jones and Donald Trump is the fact that we now have social media,' Speier continued. 'So all these people can find themselves in ways that they couldn't find themselves before.' Speier specifically cited the January 6 insurrection at the Capitol as an example of how Trump, like Jones before him, was able to mobilize a large number of supporters toward chaotic ends.

‘The treatment of your ancestors was wrong’ — After nearly 50 years, Pacific Islanders living in New Zealand finally received an apology for the ‘Dawn Raids’ 

#worldnews #newzealand #antiracism #stopasianhate #pacificislander

Attempts by House Democrats to ensure an extension of the federal eviction moratorium failed on Friday evening amid Republican objections. The moratorium expired on Saturday, leaving millions at risk of losing shelter during the pandemic, even as cases of the Delta variant surge across the country.

With the House now on a 6-week recess, the future of protections for renters remains unclear. Rep. Cori Bush and other progressive Democrats slept on the Capitol steps to urge the House to reconvene and address the looming eviction crisis.

Quinn, a 25-year-old midfielder for the Canadian women’s national soccer team, is set to become the first out transgender and/or non-binary athlete to win an Olympic medal. Canada defeated the U.S. national team on Monday, ensuring they will finish the Tokyo Games with either a gold or silver medal. Quinn, who plays professionally for the NWSL club OL Reign, also won a medal with Canada at the 2016 Games in Rio, but they were not out at the time.

‘[I’m] getting messages from young people saying they’ve never seen a trans person in sports before,’ Quinn said after the team’s victory on Monday, via CBC. ‘Athletics is the most exciting part of my life … If I can allow kids to play the sports they love, that’s my legacy and that’s what I’m here for.’
